english:
  title: Jianzhu
  author: Yun Hoe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The King speaks thus:

    Since our Grand Ancestor, the Kangon Great King, responded to Heaven's mandate and founded our realm, cultivating virtue within and repelling foes without, bringing peace to our Eastern land, the barbarians of the northern frontier—trembling at his might, yearning for his grace—wagged their tails like dogs begging for mercy. Thus within our borders, cooking smoke rose in unbroken chains, people and livestock spread across the fields, and no alarm of crowing cock or barking dog disturbed the peace.

    The Taejong, the Gongjeong Great King, inheriting the mandate and preserving the foundation, embraced all peoples with benevolent reach, subduing and binding the alien races. Island barbarians and mountain barbarians alike came to serve.

    I, unworthy of such virtue, have nonetheless upheld the wise counsels of my ancestors, nurturing the barbarians with special compassion, timely relieving their hunger and want. Yet recently, near the Pajegang, one called Yi Manjus, a dragon-lord, conspired with the rebel Yang Mudataul of the Ming, enslaving people from the Liaodong and Kaiyuan regions. These wretches, unable to bear such cruelty, fled to our land in ceaseless streams. With the sincerity of a tributary state, I returned them all to the Ming—only to have this kindness met with resentment and covetous eyes upon our territory for years.

    In the seventh month of Xuande's seventh year, taking advantage of our border's vulnerability, they burst into Gangge at Ryoenyeon, slaughtering soldiers and people, plundering livestock and treasures. Thus did they repay beneficence with betrayal, their wickedness beyond pardon. Yet they dared deceive, claiming Hulatuen led this distant banditry, while they concealed the captives and horses they seized.

    Our court, having compiled their crimes, reported to the Ming throne. This fourth month, we dispatched commanders to exact justice. Our forces advanced on multiple fronts, crushing their strongholds. Yet mindful of the warrior's restraint and the sage's mercy, we commanded our generals: should they surrender, receive them; display our might only that they may repent and fear; seek no vengeance upon the innocent.

    But the beasts would not change their nature, their savage hearts unmoved. Gathering like bees and ants, they dared resist. Our army struck where it marched to victory, beheading and capturing more than five hundred. Those who escaped death fled in scattered rout, their ranks dispersed.

    I reflect: though weapons are the tools for correcting chaos and punishing cruelty, winter and summer are not seasons to burden the people with war. Yet when Zhou's Xuan King campaigned in the sixth month against the fierce Xianyun, circumstances pressed by urgency, and none called it tyranny. These ignorant barbarians, trusting only in their treacherous terrain, violated Heaven's order and ravaged my border folk. Their calamity is self-wrought; my anger, unavoidable.

    War requires just cause; righteousness gives strength. Relying on our ancestors' sacred spirit, our soldiers advanced with fierce valor. With righteous indignation, our entire force swept into their lands. Thus the deep lairs are shattered—the very hour of the enemy's annihilation—and our frontiers purified, reaping the reward of one campaign for lasting peace.

    Let this proclamation reach all lands, that all may know.
  footnotes:
    - Kangon Great King (康獻大王) and Gongjeong Great King (恭定大王) refer to Taejo and Taejong of Joseon respectively.
    - The 'sixth month campaign' alludes to the military wisdom of ancient China's Zhou Xuan King, establishing a historical precedent for righteous warfare.
    - Xuande's seventh year places this campaign in 1432, a significant military action against Jurchen tribes.
    - The reference to 'tributary state' (事大) reflects Joseon's formal relationship with Ming China, while simultaneously asserting autonomous military authority.
